The underlying motive of these wars was oom- mercia] rivalry. They were inspired more by the desire of gain than by feelings of patriotism. With such a spirit it is no wonder that treaties were made only to be broken, 'nor does it cause surprise to learn that half a century later, when Carthago began to show signs of recovery from the blow she had received in the second war, Rome again savagely struck at her rival, and utterly destroyed her.
